///////////
Excellent question ‚Äî and you‚Äôre absolutely right to ask!

‚∏ª

üîé Why was const mockLoginId = 5 used?

That 5 was just a temporary hardcoded value (a placeholder) because in your earlier backend controller:

@PostMapping("/login")
public ResponseEntity<String> loginUser(
        @RequestParam String username,
        @RequestParam String password) {
    UserLogin user = bankService.loginUser(username, password);
    if (user != null) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok("Login successful for username: " + username);
    } else {
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.UNAUTHORIZED)
                .body("Login failed: Invalid credentials");
    }
}

You‚Äôre only returning a plain text message, like:

Login successful for username: veer

‚ö†Ô∏è This message does not contain loginId, so Angular cannot extract or store it.

‚∏ª

‚úÖ What You Should Do Instead

üîß Step 1: Change your backend to return JSON with loginId

Update your loginUser endpoint to return something like this:

@PostMapping("/login")
public ResponseEntity<Map<String, Object>> loginUser(
        @RequestParam String username,
        @RequestParam String password) {
    UserLogin user = bankService.loginUser(username, password);
    if (user != null) {
        Map<String, Object> response = new HashMap<>();
        response.put("message", "Login successful");
        response.put("loginId", user.getLoginId()); // ‚úÖ must return this!
        response.put("username", user.getUsername());
        return ResponseEntity.ok(response);
    } else {
        Map<String, Object> response = new HashMap<>();
        response.put("message", "Login failed");
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.UNAUTHORIZED).body(response);
    }
}


‚∏ª

‚úÖ Step 2: Update Angular login to store loginId

this.http.post<any>('http://localhost:8080/api/bank/login', body).subscribe({
  next: (res) => {
    if (res.loginId) {
      localStorage.setItem('loginId', res.loginId.toString());
      this.router.navigate(['/dashboard']);
    } else {
      this.message = 'Login failed!';
    }
  },
  error: () => {
    this.message = 'Login failed!';
  }
});


‚∏ª

‚úÖ Step 3: In CreateCustomerComponent (no change needed)

Since you‚Äôre already retrieving the stored loginId from localStorage in ngOnInit(), this will now work correctly.

ngOnInit() {
  const storedId = localStorage.getItem('loginId');
  this.loginId = storedId ? parseInt(storedId) : 0;
}


‚∏ª

‚úÖ Summary

Action	Why
‚úÖ Remove hardcoded 5	Because it‚Äôs just a placeholder
‚úÖ Modify backend to return loginId in JSON	So Angular can access it
‚úÖ Update frontend to read res.loginId	Store in localStorage properly

